name: methyl 3-[bis(methylsulfanyl)methyl]-4-cyano-2-hydroxy-2,5-diphenylcyclopent-3-ene-1-carboxylate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-1667
Reason: 3-[Bis(methylsulfanyl)methyl]-4-cyano-2-hydroxy-2,5-diphenylcyclopent-3-ene-1-carboxylate has a complex structure with multiple functional groups. The basic unit for comparison will be cyclopentene, which has a melting point of -109.4 degrees Celsius. The sulfur atom in the methyl group introduces a rigid structure and potential hydrogen bonding, estimated at around +20 to +30 degrees Celsius. The methyl group itself adds approximately +10 degrees Celsius due to increased molecular weight and rigidity. The cyano group introduces a strong dipole moment, which can participate in hydrogen bonding, estimated at around +30 to +50 degrees Celsius. The two phenyl groups can enhance the melting point due to pi-pi interactions and overall molecular rigidity, estimated at around +30 to +50 degrees Celsius each. The carboxyl group introduces a polar carbonyl interaction, estimated at around +20 to +30 degrees Celsius. The hydroxyl group introduces a hydrogen bonding potential, estimated at around +10 to +20 degrees Celsius. The ketone group introduces a carbonyl interaction, estimated at around +20 to +30 degrees Celsius. The methyl group introduces a rigid structure and potential hydrogen bonding, estimated at around +10 to +20 degrees Celsius.
